import java.util.*;  // Import required Java classes here! Use only those which are necessary for solution's functionality and not all possible utilities in standard library, consider using specific file handling libraries if you need a more complete example - like Apache Commons IO or Guava Util depending on your use case). Also be aware of potential security vulnerabilities while reading from files.
  
public class java_51749_FileScanner_A01 {  // Begin by naming the main program as 'Main' (lowercase for Java, but start with capital to follow PEP8 standards) and define it here! Follow standard practices in your code - like imports at top of file or comments above methods.  
    public static void printFileContents(String filename){  // Define a method that prints the contents of 'filename' if they are text documents (i.e., .txt). This is how we can read from files and not use external frameworks like Spring, Hibernate etc! Make sure you handle exceptions properly as per best practices in Java programming with try-catch blocks around file reading operations to prevent potential errors down the line - consider using java's standard library 'java.nio'.
        File f = new File(filename);  // Create a `File` instance for given filename! Important: Don’t forget about security issues while handling files and directories (like accessing different parts of file system).  
         if(!f.exists() || !f.isFile()) {    // Check whether the provided path actually exists as an ordinary non-directory item, follow PEP8 standards for naming conventions - this is a simple check to prevent possible errors down in your code later on! Important: be sure of using only standard Java methods and not external frameworks.
            System.out.println("File '" + filename+ "' does not exist or it's not actually an existing file");  // Print informative message if the path is either non-existing, directory instead a plainfile etc! Important: follow PEP8 standards for naming conventions - this comment isn’t supposed to break your code.
            return;   // End method here as there's nothing else we can do left with respect on file reading operations and error handling in mind (important!). This is a very basic example of using Java standard library only, no external dependencies or third-party libraries are allowed! – Do not use anything that will break your code if it gets compiled.
        }   // End check for whether the provided path actually exists as an ordinary non-directory item followed by return statement here to stop further execution in case of error during file reading operations (important!). This is a very basic example of using Java standard library only, no external dependencies or third party libraries are allowed! – Do not use anything that will break your code if it gets compiled.
        try(BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(f))) {   // Create `File` instance and a buffering reader for the given file (this helps to efficiently read from files). Important: be sure of using only standard Java methods, not any external library/framework.
            String line;  // Declare local variable 'line' that will hold each individual string in reading one by one until we reach end-of-file or encounter error while trying to access file content (important!). Do the same as above - be sure of using only standard Java methods, not any external library/framework.
            if(br == null) {   // Check whether 'BufferedReader' was created successfully in case it fails for some reason and throws exception during construction then catch that to prevent potential failure down further (important!). Important: do the same as above - be sure of using only standard Java methods, not any external library/framework.
                System.out.println("Cannot create BufferedReader from file '" + filename+ "'");  // Print informative message if 'Buffered Reader' was unsuccessful to construct (important!). Important: do the same as above - be sure of using only standard Java methods, not any external library/framework
                return;   // End this method here with respect on error handling in mind. This is a very basic example for file reading and exception management followed by end statement itself which ensures that if some operation fails (e.g., construction or I/O failure), the rest of your program does not get interrupted abruptly, follow PEP8 standards - this comment isn’t supposed to break my code!
            }  // End check for whether 'BufferedReader' was created successfully followed by return statement here if successful (important!). This is a very basic example only using Java standard library and no external dependencies or third-party libraries are allowed, as per instruction. Do not use anything that will cause your program to break when it gets compiled!
            while((line = br.readLine()) != null) {   // Start reading file line by line until we reach end of the text document (important!). Important: be sure about using only standard Java methods, no any external library/framework except for I/O operations which are already provided in java's BufferedReader class as part of its functionality.
                System.out.println(line);   // Print each line read from the file on console (important!). Important: be sure about using only standard Java methods, no any external library or framework except for I/O operations which are already provided in java's BufferedReader class as part of its functionality and usage restrictions mentioned above.
            }  // End reading loop if successful followed by return statement here (important!). This is a very basic example to just print contents on console from file, no security-sensitive operation or error handling included such examples can be made better according requirement - do not hesitate for more advanced ways of dealing with files and exceptions.
        }  // End try block if successful followed by end statement here (important!). This is a very basic example to just print contents on console from file, no security-sensitive operation or error handling included such examples can be made better according requirement - do not hesitate for more advanced ways of dealing with files and exceptions.
    }  // End main method if successful followed by end statement here (important!). This is a very basic example only using Java standard library which doesn’t include any external dependencies, third party libraries or frameworks as per instruction but it will work properly unless you add your own security-sensitive operations related to Broken Access Control in future.
  
}  // End of class definition (important!) - this is the main program and should be named 'Main' if not defined already followed by end statement here so that java knows where everything ends! Do note: Java requires a specific syntax for method definitions at top level, you can name your methods as per requirement but make sure they are capitalized.